    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "This is actually a [documented behavior](https://vyper.readthedocs.io/en/stable/types.html#id8). Whole numbers are integers, if you want to use those values as decimals they should be written as `2.0 / 100.0`.\r\n\r\nIf whole numbers can be interpreted as both decimals and integers, your specific example is just as likely to fold to `0` as `0.02`.  The only way to know which is the correct folding is to first type check and determine what `riskFactor` is. It also adds further ambiguity to literal arrays (`[1, 2, 3]` can now be three types), and weirdness such as:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfoo: decimal = 100\r\nbar: int128 = 2\r\n\r\nfoo / 2\r\n100 / bar\r\nfoo / bar\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe above example would raise a type mismatch at `foo / bar`, but given the previous two lines are ok, this feels like a strange outcome.",
